answers.body_markdown:
Your node insertion function has several flaws.

 1. Set `temp = head` instead of `temp-&gt;next = head`.
 2. Leave while loop too if insertion has been done.
 3. Use `if-else` for insertion position check.
 4. Both node insertion parts are not correct (invalid node linkage).
 5. Skip head and tail for list print. Start with `temp = head-&gt;next;` and use `while (temp != tail)`.

Following your insertion function with the changes to get it working.


        void SortedList::insertItem(int inData) {
            bool insert = false;
            temp = head;
            while ((temp-&gt;next != NULL) &amp;&amp; !insert) {
                if (inData &gt; temp-&gt;data) {
                    // Not the right insertion place, move forward
                    temp = temp-&gt;next;
                }
                else {
                    // Insert node in between of two nodes
                    nodePtr n = new node;
                    n-&gt;next = temp;
                    n-&gt;prev = temp-&gt;prev;
                    n-&gt;data = inData;
                    temp-&gt;prev-&gt;next = n;
                    temp-&gt;prev = n;
                    insert = true;
                }
            }
    
            // List tail reached but node has not been inserted.
            // Add node at list tail
            if (insert == false) {
                nodePtr n = new node;
                n-&gt;next = temp;
                n-&gt;prev = temp-&gt;prev;
                n-&gt;data = inData;
                temp-&gt;prev-&gt;next = n;
                tail-&gt;prev = n;
            }
    
            //Print List
            temp = head-&gt;next;
            while (temp != tail) {
                cout &lt;&lt; temp-&gt;data &lt;&lt; &quot; &quot;;
                temp = temp-&gt;next;
            }
            cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
            return;
        }

Additional notes:

 1. There is no need to add `temp` node as a member of class `SortedList`. Define it at scope where it is used.
 2. There is no need to allocate a node object for `head` and `tail`. Just use them as pointer to first and last node of list or set it to `nullptr` if list is empty.

